4.3. Database Design
--------------------

The data storage layer is implemented using a MySQL relational database. The schema is designed following normalization principles to reduce data redundancy, ensure data integrity, and provide a scalable foundation for the application.

### 4.3.1. Entity-Relationship Diagram (ERD)

The Entity-Relationship Diagram (ERD) is the master blueprint for the database. It visually represents all database tables (entities) and the logical relationships (one-to-one, one-to-many, many-to-many) between them.

The central entity is the users table, which holds all profiles and is differentiated by a role column. This table has multiple relationships:

A user (with role='admin') creates fee\_payments for a user (with role='student').

A user (with role='staff') is linked to a subject via the subject\_assignments table.

A user (with role='staff') creates assignments.

An assignment generates multiple assignment\_submissions, each linked to a user (with role='student').

marks and attendance are also logged against a user (with role='student').

A user (with role='admin') creates payment\_receipts for a user (with role='student').

